  "designDecisions": [
    "WHAT: All data in module-level singleton Maps in src/lib/store.ts (users, clients, invoices, lineItems, payments, taxRates, statusHistory, emailLogs, sessions). WHY: Zero external dependencies — runs with npm install && npm run dev, no Docker, no env vars, no migrations. Chosen over SQLite (requires better-sqlite3 native binding compilation which can fail on some environments) and over json-file (race conditions on concurrent writes). UPGRADE PATH: Each Map key corresponds directly to a Prisma model. Swap store.ts functions for Prisma client calls; shape of data is identical.",
    "WHAT: Cookie-based sessions using a Map<token, userId> in store.ts. Token is a 32-byte random hex string via Node crypto.randomBytes. Passwords stored plaintext with a comment. WHY: Zero crypto library dependencies. randomBytes is built into Node — no npm package. Plaintext passwords are acceptable for a demo/prototype; the comment in code documents the upgrade. Chosen over JWT because JWT requires jsonwebtoken or jose packages and key management. UPGRADE PATH: Replace plaintext password with bcrypt hash (npm install bcrypt). Replace session Map with Redis or DB-backed sessions. Add JWT with jose package if stateless auth is needed.",
    "WHAT: PDF generation returns a `/invoice/print/[id]` page URL instead of running Puppeteer or a PDF library. WHY: Puppeteer requires a Chromium binary (100MB+, fails on Vercel serverless). pdf-lib/pdfmake add significant bundle size and complex layout code. The print page uses Tailwind print: utilities and window.print() — browsers produce high-quality PDFs natively. The API endpoint returns { pdf_url } pointing to this printable page. UPGRADE PATH: Add @sparticuz/chromium + puppeteer-core in a dedicated /api/invoices/[id]/render route on a long-timeout serverless function or separate service.",
    "WHAT: Invoice totals (subtotal, tax_total, total, line_total) are computed server-side in invoice-utils.ts on every create/update and stored on the record. WHY: PRD requires server-side calculation to prevent client-side tampering. Storing computed values avoids re-computation on every read — critical for dashboard aggregation performance. Chosen over pure on-read computation because dashboard summary (sum of all paid invoice totals) would require re-summing all line items on every request. UPGRADE PATH: Add a DB view or materialized column in PostgreSQL.",
    "WHAT: Overdue detection runs on every GET /api/dashboard/summary request (lazy detection) in addition to an exported runOverdueCheck() function in overdue.ts. WHY: No cron/setInterval in serverless environments — timers reset on cold start and Vercel functions are stateless. The dashboard is the natural trigger point since it's loaded frequently. runOverdueCheck() is also called from middleware on a lightweight schedule check (timestamp in store). UPGRADE PATH: Add a Vercel Cron Job (vercel.json crons) calling GET /api/cron/overdue with a secret header.",
    "WHAT: Public invoice view route /invoice/view/[token] is a Next.js page (no auth) with a server component that fetches the invoice by public_token and marks it Viewed. WHY: PRD requires no-auth client access. Server component avoids a client-side fetch flash. The token is a UUIDv4 generated at invoice creation — collision-resistant without a uniqueness check in the in-memory store (crypto.randomUUID()). UPGRADE PATH: Add rate limiting middleware (upstash/ratelimit or custom IP tracking Map) on this route.",
    "WHAT: Single src/lib/store.ts exports typed accessor functions (getUser, createInvoice, etc.) rather than exposing Maps directly. WHY: Encapsulation — all mutation logic (auto-increment invoice_number, UUID generation, timestamp setting) lives in one place. Components and API routes import functions, not raw Maps, making the swap to a real DB mechanical. UPGRADE PATH: Replace each function body with the equivalent Prisma query — function signatures stay the same.",
    "WHAT: Dashboard layout in src/app/(dashboard)/layout.tsx handles auth redirect. Middleware.ts provides a secondary auth guard for /api routes. WHY: Route groups keep dashboard pages organized. Middleware runs at the edge before any page/API handler — faster rejection of unauthenticated requests. Two-layer guard: middleware blocks obviously missing cookies, layout catches edge cases and redirects. UPGRADE PATH: Move middleware to use jose JWT verification instead of store lookup when moving to stateless auth."
